<br>
Ice cores taken from Antarctica show that none such have occurred for the last 100,000 years.<br>
<br>
If a planet were close enough to collide with us in May of this year, we could already see it. Even a &quot;brown dwarf&quot; as postulated, would be visible in the infrared, and probably be picked up by x-ray detectors, as is Jupiter.<br>
<br>
A freewheeling asteroid is another matter, but too small for the catastrophe theorists.<br>
<br>
Sadly, I'm afraid that we are doomed to either live long, or die a very meager death.<br>
<br>
No wandering planets, no planetary negaspheres, no extradimensional missiles, no alien invasions...<br>
<br>
Just boredom.<br>
<br>
On the other hand...<br>
<br>
