<br>
While I will not comment on the original hypothesis, I feel compelled to discuss some other comments.<br>
<br>
I, like a great many people, do not consider the Bible to a reputable source of historical information.  The story of creation is a good place to start.   Someone earlier in the thread asked if the story had been disproved, or discredited.  The answer to this is a resounding Yes.   The age of the earth and what we know of our own prehistory discredits the story of creation.  You may chose to ignore the science involved, or even take the more radical stand point that God created a pre-aged earth with fossils already buried, and that is fine.  But you must understand that it is Your responsibility to prove the story of creation is RIGHT, not that we prove its wrong (its already been done) since you are making the assertion that it's true.<br>
<br>
The Flood.  Here is what I can only call &quot;the hypocrisy&quot; of christianity.  The ancient greeks looked at their  physical world and has questions about it that they could not answer - Why does the Sun rise?  Why do spiders build webs? etc - In an attempt to organize their world, they created Gods that supplied the answers to these questions.  We call these stories Myths. <br>
  It is perfectly reasonable to assume that in the middle east, 2000 or so years ago, people found the fossilized remains of recognizable sea creatures (they can be found everywhere, from deserts to mountain tops), and unable to answer the question of how they got there, created the Flood myth - a time when a vengeful God covered the earth with water.  We scoff at the ancient greeks, but it is politically incorrect to accuse the Catholic Church of the same mythical origins.  And that is Hypocrisy.  We know now that movement of the earth's crust makes it totally plausible that mountain tops were once sea beds.<br>
<br>
As far as towns and man made structures that now lie under water, yes it is possible that the water levels rose to cover these sites but it in no way proves that water covered the earth.  It is also equally plausible that those portions of land SANK beneath the water level.  The City of Boston is sinking a bit each day, and will one day be underwater.<br>
<br>
Why do atheists &quot;attack&quot; the beliefs of christians?  Well, in some cases it may be the one dimensional &quot;deep seated denial&quot; that Matt4Zion suggests.  And in some cases it may even be Gr8 Magus's idea that they need to make their life better, although I fail to see how that would work.  But in some cases, I know that it is because they feel that a segment of the population, who in their eyes believes in silly myths, is trying to force their views upon them.  How are they doing this?  By, trying to have Creationism taught in schools, by insisting on prayer in schools, and by the general designation of certain countries as Christian.   <br>
<br>
Is this really a problem?  That some people want to Believe?  That some people just have Faith?   It is when this faith is blind and ignores all else.  More injustice has been done, and more inhuman actions taken against fellow men, in the name of religion than anything else.  Christianity has perpetrated their fair share of this unhumanity, because people thought God was on their side.  A ridiculous idea if you ask me, and it frightens me that people who hold this belief in a myth can make decisions of world wide consequence.<br>
<br>
